From b1c0ffee5a5e4c0de0a0b0c0d0e0f00112233445 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Jiaxing Hu <huhuvmb88@outlook.com>
Date: Mon, 7 Jul 2026 12:00:00 +1200
Subject: [PATCH] pmdomain/rockchip: survive a stuck power chain on NPU warm
 power-on

On RK3576 the NPU power domains (NPUTOP -> NPU0/NPU1) are powered on
cold when the NPU is first used and then power-cycled again every time
the vendor rknpu driver re-acquires the NPU -- e.g. between two LLM
chat turns, or on the first use after a warm reboot that did not
power-cycle the SoC.

On such a WARM power-on the domain memory is still on, so
rockchip_do_pmu_set_power_domain() calls rockchip_pmu_domain_mem_reset()
to cycle the domain SRAM. Its first step polls the domain power *chain*
status, and on this SoC the NPUTOP chain never reports 'on' within the
10ms timeout:

  rockchip-pm-domain ...: failed to get chain status 'nputop', target_on=1, val=0
  RKNPU 27700000.npu: failed to get pm runtime for npu0, ret: -110

mem_reset() then returns -ETIMEDOUT, the power-on is aborted, and the
NPU driver -- which does not expect a powered-domain request to fail --
goes on to read an NPU core register on the still-unpowered core and the
CPU takes an asynchronous SError that panics the whole board.

A cold power-on (domain memory off) never runs mem_reset() at all and
works perfectly, which is exactly the state we want the warm path to
reach. The SRAM reset is a best-effort scrub; the memory is already
powered and the rknpu driver re-initialises the block on every power-on.
So when the chain-status precondition times out, warn and skip the reset
cycle rather than failing the power-on. The domain then finishes powering
on through the normal is_on poll, identically to the cold path.

Signed-off-by: Jiaxing Hu <huhuvmb88@outlook.com>
---
 drivers/pmdomain/rockchip/pm-domains.c | 12 +++++++++---
 1 file changed, 9 insertions(+), 3 deletions(-)

diff --git a/drivers/pmdomain/rockchip/pm-domains.c b/drivers/pmdomain/rockchip/pm-domains.c
index 1787f62ba..2b3c4d5e6 100644
--- a/drivers/pmdomain/rockchip/pm-domains.c
+++ b/drivers/pmdomain/rockchip/pm-domains.c
@@ -543,10 +543,17 @@ static int rockchip_pmu_domain_mem_reset(struct rockchip_pm_domain *pd)
 	ret = readx_poll_timeout_atomic(rockchip_pmu_domain_is_chain_on, pd, is_on,
 					is_on == true, 0, 10000);
 	if (ret) {
-		dev_err(pmu->dev,
-			"failed to get chain status '%s', target_on=1, val=%d\n",
-			genpd->name, is_on);
-		goto error;
+		/*
+		 * On a warm power-on (RK3576 NPU re-power) the power chain can
+		 * stay stuck off here forever. The domain memory is already on
+		 * and usable, so skip the optional SRAM reset cycle instead of
+		 * aborting the power-on: a failed power-on would leave the NPU
+		 * driver reading an unpowered core -> async SError / board panic.
+		 */
+		dev_warn_ratelimited(pmu->dev,
+			"chain status '%s' not ready, skipping mem reset\n",
+			genpd->name);
+		return 0;
 	}

 	udelay(20);
--
2.43.0
